  "prompt": "Why did Bombay turn Mumbai, Calcutta turn Kolkata?",
  "response": "The renaming of cities from Bombay to Mumbai and Calcutta to Kolkata is primarily motivated by efforts to shed remnants of colonial rule and restore indigenous names that reflect local culture, history, and languages.\n\n1. **Bombay to Mumbai:**\n   - The name \"Bombay\" is believed to have originated from the Portuguese name \"Bombaim,\" which may have been derived from the local Marathi term \"Bomb Aai\" meaning \"Good Mother.\"\n   - Mumbai was officially renamed in 1995 to reflect the Marathi heritage of the city and its people. The name \"Mumbai\" is derived from \"Mumb\u0101,\" the name of the Hindu goddess Mumbadevi, who is the city's patron deity.\n\n2. **Calcutta to Kolkata:**\n   - \"Calcutta\" is the anglicized version of \"Kolkata,\" which is derived from \"Kalikata,\" one of the three villages that predated the establishment of the city by the British East India Company.\n   - The name change to Kolkata took place in 2001 to honor the city's Bengali roots and ensure the name represents the local pronunciation in the Bengali language.\n\nBoth changes are part of broader efforts to reclaim local identity and heritage, moving away from colonial legacies and adopting names aligned with regional languages and traditions.",
